title: Grateful Dead Live at Civic Arena on 1973-09-24
description: Promised Land, Sugaree, Jack Straw, They Love Each Other, Mexicali Blues, Loose Lucy, Looks Like Rain, Row Jimmy, Big River, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Around & Around Ramble On Rose, El Paso, Mississippi Half Step, Greatest Story Ever Told, China Doll, Truckin'-> Maybe You Know-> Eyes Of The World*-> Weather Report Suite Prelude*-> Weather Report Suite Part 1*-> Let It Grow*, Sugar Magnolia

reviews.review_text: A gem from '73 This is one of the best shows I have heard from '73.  The sound quality is really good and you can hear everyone doing their part in this tight show.  The end of the second set is on a platform of greatness with the first Nobody's Fault since '66 > Eyes > WRS > Let it Grow...with Mart'n Fierro and Joe Ellis on horns as they were most of the end of '73.  Definately check out this show in any format...they all sound good.

Dead at Civic Arena, 1973 Besides the Roosevelt Stadium show in 1972 and
Capitol Theatre in 1971, this ranks as no. 3
on the East Coast for the early 70's! The release
of Wake of the Flood was only a few months old and hearing those songs live really made me
appreciate them.

Dont do it!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! I honestly do not know what the other reviewers were listening to when they wrote there reviews but the sound quality is awful. Not recommended! From what I listened to the songs are executed well but the quality is so bad I had to shut it off. Hardcore Heads only.

Lucky find, poor quality Well, Nuggets was right, this is unfortunately a very poor sounding recording of a good show.

I have a recording off my local radio station of an Eyes with horns that got cut because my tape ran out.  I've always wanted to hear the end of that Eyes because it was really good.  

Well, I search archive.org for "Grateful Dead horns" and here I am.  This is the Eyes I wanted to find.  Too bad the sound quality of this show isn't up to par, but I'm glad I finally know which show this is from and thanks to Candyman for letting me know who was playing horns.

There are other much-better sounding recordings and just-as-good shows around.  Thanks, archive.
